{
  "text": "The observation that the PWWP domain binds histones and DNA in separate regions raised the possibility that this domain may simultaneously interact with methylated histone tails and nucleosomal DNA. A GST-pull down assay demonstrated that the PWWP domain of the S. pombe protein Pdp1 directly interacts with isolated yeast nucleosomes [CITATION_1] ). In addition, the PWWP domain of DNMT3a is able to pull down native nucleosomes purified from human cells [CITATION_2] . Direct nucleosomal binding has been shown to a variety of PWWP-containing proteins, including Pdp1 [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , DNMT3a [CITATION_5] , Ioc4 [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , LEDGF/p75 [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , and ZMNYD11 [CITATION_10] . In all cases, nucleosomal interaction is enhanced by histone methylation. The PWWP domain of Pdp1 interacts with nucleosomes purified from wild-type yeast cells, but not with those from strains carrying the histone methyltransferase Set9 deletion or the H4K20R mutation, indicating that Pdp1 PWWP specifically recognizes H4K20me [CITATION_11] ). Similarly, the PWWP domain of DNMT3a specifically interacts with nucleosomes harboring the H3K36me3 mark [CITATION_12] .",
  "correct_citation": {
